---
// Serial — "The S12 Silvia — Initial D's Biggest Snub."
// Second real article after the Nikon FE2 piece. User-sourced photos of
// their own S12 (an RS-X Turbo, "Full White" livery) dropped into
// _incoming. The Initial D framing — every notable 80s/90s Nissan coupe
// got a moment in the show except the car that started the Silvia line —
// is the author's own fan-opinion premise, not an encyclopedia claim, so
// it's written in first-person voice rather than asserted as fact.
import SerialLayout from "../../layouts/SerialLayout.astro";
import Nav from "../../components/serial/Nav.astro";
import Hero from "../../components/serial/Hero.astro";
import ImageGrid from "../../components/serial/ImageGrid.astro";
import ArticleSection from "../../components/serial/ArticleSection.astro";
import PullQuote from "../../components/serial/PullQuote.astro";
import LensSpec from "../../components/serial/LensSpec.astro";
import RatingStrip from "../../components/serial/RatingStrip.astro";
import RelatedGrid from "../../components/serial/RelatedGrid.astro";
import Paywall from "../../components/serial/Paywall.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/serial/Footer.astro";
---

<SerialLayout
	title="The S12 Silvia — Initial D's Biggest Snub — Serial"
	description="A case for the Nissan Silvia S12: the coupe that started the whole Silvia line, and the one Initial D never gave a garage spot."
>
	<Nav />

	<Hero
		kicker="Drive / JDM"
		category="Feature"
		title="The S12 Silvia — Initial D's Biggest Snub"
		image={{ src: "/images/serial/hero-s12-silvia.jpg", alt: "Rear three-quarter view of a white Nissan Silvia S12 parked in tall grass among trees, showing the SILVIA badge and S12 numberplate" }}
	/>

	<div class="wrap">
		<div class="section" style="padding-top:56px">
			<p class="lede">
				<span class="drop">Every self-respecting 80s and 90s Japanese sports coupe got its moment in Initial D</span> —
				S13, S14, S15, even a Sileighty stitched together from two different Nissans. The car that started the whole
				Silvia lineage never showed up. That's not an oversight. That's a snub.
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>

	<ImageGrid
		variant="2"
		tiles={[
			{
				image: { src: "/images/serial/s12-front-sunset.jpg", alt: "The Nissan Silvia S12 photographed front three-quarter at dusk, suburban houses in the background" },
			},
			{
				image: { src: "/images/serial/s12-profile-palms.jpg", alt: "Side profile of the white Nissan Silvia S12, parked in front of palm trees and a concrete wall" },
			},
		]}
	/>

	<ArticleSection number="01" title="The Silvia Nobody Cast">
		<p>
			The S12 is the second-generation Silvia — the one that came before the S13 the entire drift world, and Initial
			D along with it, decided to worship. Wedge-nosed, pop-up headlights, a name badge that still reads clean forty
			years later. It's not obscure by accident. It's obscure because the show that made every other Nissan coupe a
			household name for a certain kind of car kid simply skipped it.
		</p>
		<p>
			By the time Initial D was casting its garage of legends, the S12 had already aged out of relevance in the
			culture's eyes — too early for the touge scene the show was built around, overshadowed by everything that came
			directly after it. Which is a shame, because underneath the boxy early-80s shape is a genuinely serious piece
			of engineering.
		</p>
	</ArticleSection>

	<ImageGrid
		variant="wide"
		tiles={[
			{
				aspect: "16 / 6",
				image: {
					src: "/images/serial/s12-night-fence.jpg",
					alt: "The Silvia S12 parked at night beside a chain-link fence and an ENTER ONLY, STRICTLY SMOKE FREE ZONE sign, lit dramatically against a starry sky",
				},
			},
		]}
	/>

	<PullQuote
		quote="A boosted coupe that could plausibly run down the Panda Trueno on a straight wouldn't have made for a very good underdog story."
	/>

	<ArticleSection number="02" title="RS-X Full White">
		<p>
			This one's the RS-X Turbo — the trim that actually deserved a highlight reel. Under the hood is the FJ20ET, a
			twin-cam 2.0-liter turbo four that was, on paper, a genuinely quick engine for 1985. Nissan wasn't dabbling
			with turbo Silvias as a marketing gimmick; the FJ20ET was a serious motor, and the RS-X Full White package
			dressed it in a livery that still looks better than half of what rolled off dealer lots a decade later.
		</p>
		<p>
			Drive one and the character is obvious immediately — that particular turbo-lag-then-shove rhythm that later,
			more refined Silvias smoothed out of existence. It's rawer than an S13, rougher around the edges, and more
			honest about what it is: an early-80s turbo coupe that hasn't been sanded down by forty years of nostalgia
			marketing.
		</p>
	</ArticleSection>

	<ImageGrid
		variant="2"
		tiles={[
			{
				image: { src: "/images/serial/s12-decal-detail.jpg", alt: "Close-up of the RS-X Full White, Twin Cam Turbo decal on the Silvia S12's front door" },
			},
			{
				image: { src: "/images/serial/s12-interior.jpg", alt: "The Silvia S12's interior, showing the steering wheel, manual shifter, and dashboard controls" },
			},
		]}
	/>

	<ArticleSection number="03" title="Could It Hang With the Panda Trueno?">
		<p>
			Here's the theory, and I'll own that it's a theory: the S12 never got its Initial D moment because it might
			have actually given the AE86 a real fight.
		</p>
		<p>
			Takumi's Trueno is a 1.6-liter naturally aspirated 4A-GE making somewhere around 130 horsepower stock, running
			on downhill momentum, tofu-delivery muscle memory, and one of the greatest underdog stories animation has ever
			told. It deserves every bit of its legend status. But horsepower for horsepower, an RS-X Turbo S12 is putting
			out meaningfully more from the factory — turbocharged instead of screaming to redline for it, on the same
			basic front-engine, rear-wheel-drive recipe.
		</p>
		<p>
			Maybe that's exactly why it stayed out of the show. Easier to leave it out of the garage entirely than let it
			complicate the myth.
		</p>
	</ArticleSection>

	<LensSpec
		name="Nissan Silvia S12 — RS-X Turbo"
		sn="1983&ndash;1988 &middot; FR chassis"
		rows={[
			{ k: "Engine", v: "FJ20ET 2.0L turbo I4" },
			{ k: "Power", v: "~190hp (JDM RS-X)" },
			{ k: "Layout", v: "Front-engine, RWD" },
		]}
		verdict="Underrated"
	>
		More power than the car everyone remembers, from the same basic recipe, wearing a livery that still holds up.
		The one that got left out of the garage.
	</LensSpec>

	<LensSpec
		name="Toyota AE86 — Trueno / Levin"
		sn="1983&ndash;1987 &middot; FR chassis"
		rows={[
			{ k: "Engine", v: "4A-GE 1.6L NA I4" },
			{ k: "Power", v: "~130hp (stock)" },
			{ k: "Layout", v: "Front-engine, RWD" },
		]}
		verdict="The legend"
	>
		Deserves every bit of its status — the tofu shop, the downhill runs, the whole underdog story. Just not
		necessarily the faster car.
	</LensSpec>

	<RatingStrip
